>>>>>> Creating a new folder in a Git repository <<<<<<


A. Open the Git repository in a terminal or command prompt.


B. Navigate to the directory where you want to create the new folder.


C. Use the mkdir command to create a new directory with your desired folder name. For example, to create a folder named "new_folder", type the following command:

$ mkdir new_folder


D. Use the git add command to stage the new folder and its contents for commit. For example, to stage the new_folder directory, type the following command:

$ git add new_folder


E. Use the git commit command to commit the changes to the repository. For example, to commit the new_folder directory, type the following command:

$ git commit -m "Added new_folder directory"


D. Finally, use the git push command to push the changes to the remote repository. For example, to push the changes to the default remote branch (usually "master"), type the following command:

$ git push origin master